      Buffer fund
   =20
 =20

A well-known bit of derivatives magic =E2=80=94=C2=A0a great, simple party =
trick that derivatives structurers can use to impress their friends =E2=80=
=94 is that if you give me $100 today, I can invest $91=C2=A0of it in two-y=
ear Treasury notes paying 4.75% interest, and in two years I will have $100=
.
  [1]
 And I can invest the other $9 in two-year at-the-money
  [2]
 call options on the S&P 500 stock index, options that gain value if the S&=
P goes up over those two years. Those options cost, let=E2=80=99s say, 13% =
of the price of the S&P today,
  [3]
=C2=A0so spending $9 on options will get me an option on about $70 worth of=
 the index. And so I can offer you the following trade:
=09You give me $100 today.=09In two years, I give you back (1) $100, no mat=
ter what,=C2=A0plus (2) 70% of the return on the S&P 500 index, if it=E2=80=
=99s up.

If stocks go up, you get the gains (well, 70% of them). If stocks go down, =
you don=E2=80=99t get the losses. What a great trade!
And because I can do this efficiently in size, and because I thought of it =
and you didn=E2=80=99t, and because I advertised it to you with a cool broc=
hure, I can charge you like 1% of your money for putting this trade togethe=
r. It is a very good trade, honestly. If you are a sophisticated investor y=
ou can quibble with it,
  [4]
 but at a simple intuitive level it is just nice. =E2=80=9CYou get [much of=
] the upside of stocks, but no downside=E2=80=9D is a clean and satisfying =
pitch. The shape of the payoff graph is pleasing.=C2=A0
Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=C2=A0Vildana Hajric and Emily Graffeo report:

The pioneer of the world=E2=80=99s first =E2=80=9Cbuffer ETFs=E2=80=9D =E2=
=80=94 exchange-traded funds that are supposed to limit losses during marke=
t selloffs =E2=80=94 has launched a new product which it says offers invest=
ors complete downside protection.
Investors in the $7.5 trillion ETF universe can now put money behind the In=
novator Equity Defined Protection ETF, which began trading under the ticker=
 TJUL on Tuesday. The offering comes from Innovator Capital Management, whi=
ch launched the first so-called buffer ETFs, also sometimes referred to as =
defined-outcome funds, in 2018.
Buffer funds, as the name suggests, offer buffered exposure to stocks by li=
miting investors=E2=80=99 downside risk while also capping upside potential=
. =E2=80=A6
Yet, Innovator says that its TJUL fund =E2=80=94 which will track S&P 500 r=
eturns up to a capped percentage over a two-year period =E2=80=94 will be t=
he first of its kind to protect against 100% of stock losses. TJUL=E2=80=99=
s cap on potential gains is estimated at about 15% after fees.
Specifically, the fund will invest at least 80% of its net assets in option=
s on the $423 billion SPDR S&P 500 ETF Trust (ticker SPY), according to the=
 fund=E2=80=99s prospectus. TJUL can purchase and sell a combination of cal=
l and put options in an effort to cushion against market volatility.
The outcomes set by the fund may only be realized by investors who continuo=
usly hold shares of TJUL from the first day of the =E2=80=9Coutcome period=
=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 July 18 =E2=80=94 to the end of the two-year period, wh=
ich is June 30, 2025, reads the prospectus.=C2=A0

They give you 100% of the gains up to the cap, rather than 70% of uncapped =
gains, but same basic idea.
  [5]

There is a reason that this product is the first of its kind: If interest r=
ates are zero, I can=E2=80=99t invest $91 in Treasuries to get back $100, s=
o I don=E2=80=99t have $9 to spend on options to get S&P 500 upside. (I hav=
e to put, like, $99 in Treasuries, and the only way to get you any meaningf=
ul upside is by giving you some downside risk too.) But as interest rates h=
ave gone up, products like this look better, and so people are offering the=
m.=C2=A0
Of course as interest rates have gone up, products like this are in some se=
nse=C2=A0less attractive: Putting up $100 and getting back $100 in two year=
s is worse=C2=A0if I missed out on 4.75% interest than it would be if inter=
est rates were zero.
  [6]
=C2=A0But that=E2=80=99s not the point! The point is that a trade like =E2=
=80=9CI will give you some stock upside and take 75% of the downside betwee=
n down 5% and down 20% blah blah blah=E2=80=9D is annoying and complicated,=
 while =E2=80=9CI will give you the upside of stocks and you can=E2=80=99t =
lose any money=E2=80=9D is nice and simple and intuitively attractive. =E2=
=80=9CBuffer fund=E2=80=9D is complicated, =E2=80=9Cstock fund but you can=
=E2=80=99t lose money=E2=80=9D has an obvious appeal.

