      Fisker
   =20
 =20

Fisker Inc. is an electric-vehicle company. It went public by merging with =
a special purpose acquisition company in 2020, back in the electric-vehicle=
-SPAC boom; its stock got as high as $28.50 per share (a market capitalizat=
ion of about $7.9 billion) in 2021 but closed yesterday at $6.55 ($2.2 bill=
ion). It =E2=80=9Chas yet to generate  any significant revenue from its cor=
e business operations,=E2=80=9D lost about $547 million last year and =E2=
=80=9Cexpects to continue to incur significant operating losses for the for=
eseeable future.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0It had $652 million of cash as of March 31.
People love electric-vehicle stocks, or at least they used to, so Fisker to=
ps up its cash by selling stock. Last year it announced an  at-the-market o=
ffering in which it would sell up to $350 million of stock, on the stock ex=
change, at market prices; it  terminated that offering last week after sell=
ing about $327 million of stock. It replaced that plan with a new, far more=
 complicated plan to sell between $340 million and $680 million worth of st=
ock. (Here is  the 8-K announcing this plan, and here is=C2=A0 the prospect=
us.) It goes something like this:
=09Fisker sold =E2=80=9Csenior convertible notes due 2025=E2=80=9D to a sin=
gle investor, who is not identified. These notes have a face value of $340 =
million, but the investor got them at a discount, paying Fisker $300 millio=
n.=09The investor can convert the notes to stock, any time it wants,=C2=A0a=
t a price of $7.80 per share, a 30% premium to the $6 stock price just befo=
re the notes offering.=09Also, though, =E2=80=9Cthe Notes amortize in nine =
equal [quarterly] installments starting on July=C2=A011,=C2=A02023=E2=80=9D=
 (that is, the day after they were issued). Each quarter, $37,777,777 worth=
 of notes come due, and Fisker can elect to pay them off (1) in cash at 103=
% of face value (i.e. $38.9 million per quarter) or (2) in stock, at a spec=
ial conversion price.=09The special conversion price is (1) floored at abou=
t $1.16=C2=A0per share,
  [7]
 (2) capped at $7.80 per share (the conversion price), and (3) otherwise 93=
% of the volume-weighted average price of Fisker=E2=80=99s stock on either =
the day before conversion or the five days before conversion (whichever is =
lower).=09Starting next July, the investor can choose to buy another $226.7=
 million of notes on the same terms, and if it does the company can choose =
to sell it another $113.3 million of notes, for a maximum of $340 million m=
ore ($680 million total).

The result is that, if the stock stays roughly where it is today, each quar=
ter Fisker delivers about $40.6 million worth of stock to the investor, whi=
ch the investor can immediately sell into the market.
  [8]
 In total, Fisker gives the investor about $365.6 million worth of stock in=
 nine quarterly installments, and the investor gives Fisker $300 million no=
w. Fisker has the option to pay the investor back in cash instead of stock =
if it wants (paying back a total of $350 million in cash
  [9]
), and the investor has the option of converting all of its bonds into stoc=
k worth even more than $365 million if the stock goes above $7.80 per share=
.
  [10]
=C2=A0
Also, =E2=80=9Cthe Investor can defer an installment payment due on any ins=
tallment date to another installment date and may, on any installment date =
accelerate the payment of amounts due on up to an additional two times the =
installment payment of the Notes=E2=80=9D: The investor has some additional=
 optionality to get a lot of stock when the getting is good, or to skip som=
e stock deliveries when it is bad.
I don=E2=80=99t know who the investor is here or what they are thinking, bu=
t when you see a trade like this a reasonable guess is that the investor is=
 not planning to convert into stock and hold it as a large long-term invest=
or in Fisker. (In fact, the investor is not=C2=A0allowed=C2=A0to do that: T=
he notes can=E2=80=99t be converted if any conversion would leave it with m=
ore than 4.99% of Fisker=E2=80=99s stock, or about $112 million worth of st=
ock at current prices.) Instead, the reasonable assumption is that the inve=
stor plans to get about $40.6 million worth of stock each quarter and sell =
it, more or less immediately, at market prices, on the stock exchange; when=
 it has finished with that, it will come back for more the next quarter.
In other words, this=C2=A0is=C2=A0kind of an at-the-market stock offering, =
except that Fisker gets the money upfront,
  [11]
=C2=A0and the investor gets a fee of something like 20% for its efforts (an=
d for advancing the cash).
If this sounds familiar, it is broadly similar to     the trade that Bed Ba=
th & Beyond Inc. did earlier this year to sell stock. In each case, there i=
s a weird instrument that looks like a convertible security, and a big =E2=
=80=9Cinvestor=E2=80=9D who is buying most or all of it. But in each case, =
the buyer is not really set up to be a long-term investor in the company: T=
he investor=C2=A0is getting the stock in installments, at a discount to mar=
ket value, and selling each installment to retail investors on the stock ex=
change.=C2=A0And the investor is getting paid a nice fee for structuring th=
e trade, giving the company=C2=A0the money upfront, and generally obscuring=
 what is happening. =E2=80=9CWe are selling $365 million of stock to retail=
 investors to raise $300 million=E2=80=9D just sounds less good than =E2=80=
=9Cwe are selling a $340 million convertible with a 30% conversion premium =
to a big investor.=E2=80=9D

 =20
   =20
      Co-invests
   =20
 =20

If you are a big sovereign wealth fund, private equity firms will call you =
up a lot to ask you to invest in their new fund. =E2=80=9CGive us $1 billio=
n,=E2=80=9D they will say, =E2=80=9Cand we will invest it in the deals we p=
ick and charge you a 2% fee plus 20% of profits.=E2=80=9D And you might cou=
nter: =E2=80=9CNo, you go pick the deals and bring them to us, and if we li=
ke them we will invest in them, and if we don=E2=80=99t we won=E2=80=99t, a=
nd either way we won=E2=80=99t pay you a fee.=E2=80=9D And then you=E2=80=
=99ll   negotiate a compromise:
As private equity fundraising becomes more difficult, [sovereign wealth fun=
ds are] asking for guaranteed access to deal flow in return for providing c=
apital to a new fund, according to industry participants. This extra money =
they provide on the side for co-investments usually has the added benefit o=
f not being subject to management fees.
Basically: =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99ll give you $500 million to invest in whatev=
er deals you want and charge us fees, but in exchange you have to bring us =
$1 billion of deals that we get to say yes or no to and=C2=A0not=C2=A0charg=
e us fees.=E2=80=9D That is from a Bloomberg News article about sovereign w=
ealth funds co-investing in private equity deals:

KKR & Co., EQT AB and Brookfield all turned to wealthy Persian Gulf countri=
es to stump up a lot of the money for big-ticket deals in recent weeks. Sov=
ereign wealth funds spent a record $17.2 billion on such co-investments in =
the first half, up 24% from the same period last year, according to data pr=
ovider Global SWF.
While teaming up on deals isn=E2=80=99t unusual, the amount of equity these=
 state-backed investors are providing has jumped as buyout firms find debt =
more expensive. =E2=80=A6
=E2=80=9CSWFs can often move very quickly, can be flexible and have large a=
mounts of capital =E2=80=94 they can be an extremely useful capital provide=
r,=E2=80=9D said Elizabeth Todd, a partner at law firm Ropes & Gray. =E2=80=
=9CWhere they find an asset they like, they do not feel limited to small mi=
nority investments with passive governance rights.=E2=80=9D
A senior executive at a top global sovereign fund said they=E2=80=99re enco=
uraging buyout firms to pursue larger acquisitions even in this tight finan=
cing market. They=E2=80=99ve expressed their willingness to back deals with=
 bigger equity checks to reduce the burden on the acquirer, the person said=
, adding that their fund has to join more of these transactions to achieve =
its higher private equity allocation.

In principle, the private equity funds could do bigger deals, and the SWFs =
could get their higher private equity allocations, if the SWFs just investe=
d more money in the private equity funds to begin with. But that means more=
 fees and less flexibility for the SWFs, and if you have a lot of money you=
 do not need to =E2=80=9Cfeel limited to small minority investments with pa=
ssive governance rights.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0

 =20
   =20
      Congressional stock ownership
   =20
 =20

Well  this is popular:

Two U.S. senators are set this week to introduce bipartisan legislation to =
bar members of the federal executive branch and lawmakers from owning stock=
 in individual companies, as new polling shows broad public support for suc=
h a measure.
The bill from Sens. Kirsten Gillibrand (D., N.Y.) and Josh Hawley (R., Mo.)=
 would permit the president, vice president, lawmakers, Capitol Hill aides =
and employees of the executive branch to own mutual funds and broad industr=
y and index funds.=C2=A0
But it would prohibit them from owning stocks in individual companies, even=
 in blind trusts. =E2=80=A6
The new bill would outright ban ownership of individual stocks by members o=
f Congress and their aides. Lawmakers and their aides are currently permitt=
ed to own and trade individual stocks as long as they don=E2=80=99t make in=
vestment decisions based on nonpublic information they learn from their job=
s in Congress. ...
A poll released Wednesday by the University of Maryland=E2=80=99s Program f=
or Public Consultation found that 80% of voters support a ban on stock owne=
rship by members of Congress, the president, vice president, Supreme Court =
justices and their families. The survey of 2,625 registered voters has a ma=
rgin of error of plus or minus 1.9%.
=E2=80=9CWhile the prospect of a stock-trading ban is controversial within =
Congress, public support approaches unanimity,=E2=80=9D said Steven Kull, t=
he director of the Program for Public Consultation.=C2=A0

I hate to be like =E2=80=9CI agree with the thing that 80% of people agree =
with,=E2=80=9D because that isn=E2=80=99t very interesting, is it, but I th=
ink I agree? If you own individual stocks then:
=09You might get inside information, through your government job, and trade=
 on it;=09You might make=C2=A0decisions, at your government job, that favor=
 the companies whose stocks you own; and=09You might be distracted from you=
r government job by day-trading all your stocks.

Of course there are finely tailored ways to address all of those risks, but=
 =E2=80=9Cjust don=E2=80=99t own individual stocks=E2=80=9D seems pretty st=
raightforward. Also I have never fully understood =E2=80=9Cblind trusts=E2=
=80=9D but my understanding is that a lot of government officials own a ton=
 of stock in, like, the company they used to work for, and they put that st=
ock in a =E2=80=9Cblind trust=E2=80=9D run by a broker who has discretion t=
o sell it, and then they leave the government five years later and, surpris=
e, all the stock is still in the trust. (Donald Trump, absurdly, put his st=
ake in his=C2=A0private company with his name on it=C2=A0in a =E2=80=9Cblin=
d trust=E2=80=9D run by=C2=A0his children.=C2=A0It would have been very fun=
ny if they sold the company and put all the money in index funds, but they =
did not.)=C2=A0
I suppose the objections are:
=09It is nice to be able to attract accomplished people to government servi=
ce, and some number of accomplished people will have a lot of stock in thei=
r former employers that they are unable or unwilling to sell. (Or: Their=C2=
=A0spouses=C2=A0might own a lot of stock that they can=E2=80=99t or won=E2=
=80=99t sell.)=09A lot of the =E2=80=9Cinside information=E2=80=9D that gov=
ernment officials get is fairly=C2=A0macroeconomic, and so can be misused b=
y trading index funds. If you got   bad top-secret news about the severity =
of Covid-19 before everyone else did, you could have been crafty and sold c=
ruise-ship stocks while buying teleconferencing stocks, but just dumping al=
l of your index funds would have worked fine too.


 =20
   =20
      Terra
   =20
 =20

Sure, I don=E2=80=99t know,  whatever:

Terraform Labs has named a new chief executive officer to run the crypto co=
mpany while its co-founder Do Kwon faces fraud charges stemming from the $4=
0 billion collapse of the TerraUSD and Luna cryptocurrencies.
The interim CEO is Chris Amani, who was previously the company=E2=80=99s ch=
ief operating officer and chief financial officer, Terraform Labs told The =
Wall Street Journal.=C2=A0
Terraform Labs is trying to show that it is business as usual while the com=
pany=E2=80=99s former CEO is jailed in the Balkan country of Montenegro. Bo=
th the U.S. and Kwon=E2=80=99s native South Korea are seeking his extraditi=
on.=C2=A0
The company is pressing on with a long-shot bid to revive the Terra blockch=
ain that underpinned the failed cryptocurrencies. Amani said the company wo=
uld develop applications =E2=80=9Cthat provide real utility=E2=80=9D and wo=
uld share more details of its plans in the coming months.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CWe have a vision for how we could salvage this, even though I thin=
k it=E2=80=99s going to be hard and it=E2=80=99s going to take a long time,=
=E2=80=9D Amani said in an interview. =E2=80=A6
=E2=80=9CWe wish Do the best and we hope that he=E2=80=99s able to clear hi=
mself of all charges. But while he=E2=80=99s incarcerated and while he=E2=
=80=99s facing his own legal challenges, it just makes sense for us to cont=
inue on without him,=E2=80=9D Amani said.

And FTX keeps talking about  restarting its crypto exchange even as its fou=
nder, Sam Bankman-Fried, is, uh, facing his own legal challenges. And the T=
hree Arrows Capital guys =E2=80=94=C2=A0who are=C2=A0not=C2=A0facing legal =
challenges,   which a lot of people find surprising=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0hav=
e  their own new crypto exchange. What if it all works? What if in 10 years=
 the big respectable crypto incumbents are New FTX and New Terra, while the=
ir founders are in prison?=C2=A0
That would be funny? I think a lot about a dynamic among startup founders: =
High-profile founders tend to make grandiose promises and claims that do no=
t quite match reality, and then either (1) it works out and they are hailed=
 as visionary geniuses or (2) it doesn=E2=80=99t and they are arrested.=C2=
=A0It would be odd if crypto found a third option, where the founders are a=
rrested but it all ultimately works out.
Of course FTX and Terra manifestly did not=C2=A0work out, in that they coll=
apsed and cost their investors a lot of money. If you are an ambitious cryp=
to person and you want to build the world=E2=80=99s leading crypto exchange=
 or whatever-Terra-is, if you want to =E2=80=9Cprovide real utility=E2=80=
=9D and attract a lot of users and investors =E2=80=A6=C2=A0wouldn=E2=80=99=
t it be better to start from zero? Instead of starting way in the hole, lik=
e Terra and FTX are?
Part of the issue is that both FTX and Terra issued=C2=A0tokens, and the be=
st way to recover value for their customers is to make those tokens valuabl=
e again. If FTX restarts successfully, then its FTT tokens will be valuable=
 again, and FTX has tons of those tokens and can use them to pay back its c=
ustomers. There is some built-in base of investors who (1) were (allegedly)=
 defrauded by the company but (2) are incentivized to root for its success.=
 Still it feels like a weird marketing pitch.
 Elsewhere:

Zhe =E2=80=9CConstance=E2=80=9D Wang, who served in several executive-level=
 roles at Sam Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s FTX before the collapse of the digita=
l-asset exchange, has joined crypto venture capital firm Sino Global Capita=
l.
Wang leads the gaming team at Sino Global, according to Matthew Graham, a B=
eijing-based investor who founded Sino Global in 2015 and had previously wo=
rked at China Bridge Capital.
Wang was the chief operating officer of FTX and co-chief executive officer =
of FTX Digital Markets, the bankrupt crypto exchange=E2=80=99s Bahamas affi=
liate. Wang=E2=80=99s responsibilities included leading the exchange=E2=80=
=99s global business expansion, oversight of token listings and public rela=
tions and marketing, according to her LinkedIn profile.

On the one hand, which of FTX=E2=80=99s operations were=C2=A0good?=C2=A0On =
the other hand, sure, why not? If you are a crypto venture capital firm, on=
e of your main risks is investing in a giant fraud. If you hire someone who=
 worked at an alleged giant fraud, she might be helpful in due diligence.

