  [1] Not precise but you know what I mean, $91 x (1.0475)^2 =3D 100ish. Re=
ally you=E2=80=99d do this with STRIPS to avoid reinvestment risk.


  [2] By =E2=80=9Cat-the-money=E2=80=9D I mean that the S&P 500 is at about=
 4,570 this morning, so I would buy an option struck at 4,570; I am looking=
 at the 4,550 and 4,600 strikes on June 2025 call options (on Bloomberg pag=
e SPX Index CALL). Derivatives people sometimes use =E2=80=9Cat-the-money=
=E2=80=9D more technically to mean the option struck at the forward price (=
higher than today=E2=80=99s price due to interest rates), but that is not t=
he intuitive use that gets you the nice product here.


  [3] Again, those $4,550 and $4,600 June 2025 calls seem to trade at about=
 $570, from Bloomberg, so in the neighborhood of 12.5% of notional; I am ro=
unding up. June 2025 call options on SPY, the S&P 500 exchange-traded fund,=
 seem to be at about $60 for the $455 strike (roughly today=E2=80=99s spot =
price), or about 13.1% of notional. These numbers are not meant to be all t=
hat precise.


  [4] I mean two obvious quibbles are (1) if you buy stocks, you get not on=
ly the price return but also the dividends; the S&P 500 has about a 1.5% di=
vidend yield, and (2) if you *don=E2=80=99t* buy stocks, you get a 4.75% yi=
eld on Treasuries, so your risk-free investment pays you like $110 in two y=
ears. If stocks are down, this trade is worse than just buying Treasuries, =
and if stocks are up this trade is worse than just buying stocks, and if st=
ocks are flat this trade is worse than any mix of buying stocks and buying =
Treasuries.=20


  [5] If I just look at June 2025 call options on SPY, the $455 strike (rou=
ghly today=E2=80=99s price) costs about $60, and the $525 strike (roughly u=
p 15%) costs about $20, per Bloomberg (SPY US Equity CALL). So the net cost=
 of the call spread =E2=80=94 buy the at-the-money, sell the up 15% =E2=80=
=94 is about $40, or about 8.8% of notional, which is pretty much what I=E2=
=80=99d have left over after putting 91% of your money into Treasuries.


  [6] Also the cap is less attractive with higher rates. If the two-year ri=
sk-free rate is 4.75% and the equity risk premium is 6%, then over two year=
s the expected return on the S&P 500 is something like 22.7%, meaning that =
your capped 15% return would be disappointing.=20


  [7] The floor price is not stated in the prospectus, but the prospectus c=
overs =E2=80=9Cup to 293,103,448 shares of Class A Common Stock issuable fr=
om time to time upon conversion or otherwise under the Notes, assuming conv=
ersion at a conversion price equal to the Floor Price,=E2=80=9D and if you =
divide $340 million by 293.1 million you get about $1.16.


  [8] =E2=80=9CImmediately=E2=80=9D understates it: The rational move for t=
he investor is to sell the stock into the market *before* each amortization=
 date, over the one- or five-day VWAP period. You sell the stock short, try=
ing to match the VWAP; you realize exactly $40.6 million on your sales; you=
 exercise and get exactly enough stock to close out your short. The choice =
of one- or five-day VWAP gives you some flexibility to sell quickly (if the=
 volume supports it) or slowly (if it doesn=E2=80=99t). These days Fisker=
=E2=80=99s stock trades about $48 million per day, so you=E2=80=99d want at=
 least five days to sell your $40.6 million of stock, and it might take you=
 a bit longer (that is, you might not plan to perfectly hedge before conver=
ting). The choice also gives you some extra optionality: If you sell over f=
ive days and the one-day VWAP is lower, you get some bonus stock.


  [9] That is, the $340 million face amount times 103% of face amount for c=
ash amortization payments.


  [10] Actually the stock has to get to about $8.39 for this to be a good d=
eal for the investor: Converting at $7.80 per share gets you 43.6 million s=
hares ($340 million divided by $7.80), whereas converting at 93% of market =
value gets you $365.6 million worth of stock, and $365.6 divided by 43.6 is=
 $8.39.=20


  [11] This gives it a bit more certainty of proceeds than a regular ATM wo=
uld give it: If the stock goes way down, it still has the money. But not mu=
ch more: There are a lot of conditions and covenants, and if the stock does=
 go way down there=E2=80=99s a decent chance Fisker will have to pay the in=
vestor back in cash rather than stock. There is also a covenant that Fisker=
 =E2=80=9C will maintain a balance of available cash (as defined in the Not=
es) equal to or greater than $340,000,000,=E2=80=9D so it can=E2=80=99t exa=
ctly blow through all the cash it raised before the two-year period is up.


