<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Buffer fund</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A well-known bit of derivatives magic =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0a great, simple party trick that derivatives structurers can use t=
o impress their friends =E2=80=94 is that if you give me $100 today, I can =
invest $91=C2=A0of it in two-year Treasury notes paying 4.75% interest, and=
 in two years I will have $100.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnot=
e-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !imp=
ortant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a> And I can invest the other $9 in two-year at-the-money<a class=3D"foot=
note-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !importan=
t; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a> call options on the S&amp;P 500 stock index, options that gain value i=
f the S&amp;P goes up over those two years. Those options cost, let=E2=80=
=99s say, 13% of the price of the S&amp;P today,<a class=3D"footnote-index"=
 href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display:=
 inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0so spending $9 on options will get me an option on about $70 wort=
h of the index. And so I can offer you the following trade:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You give me $100 today.</li>=09<li sty=
le=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">In two years, I give you back (1) $100, no matte=
r what,=C2=A0plus (2) 70% of the return on the S&amp;P 500 index, if it=E2=
=80=99s up.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If stocks go up, you get the gains (well, 70% =
of them). If stocks go down, you don=E2=80=99t get the losses. What a great=
 trade!</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And because I can do this efficiently in size,=
 and because I thought of it and you didn=E2=80=99t, and because I advertis=
ed it to you with a cool brochure, I can charge you like 1% of your money f=
or putting this trade together. It is a very good trade, honestly. If you a=
re a sophisticated investor you can quibble with it,<a class=3D"footnote-in=
dex" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; disp=
lay: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a> but at a simple intuitive level it is just nice. =E2=80=9CYou get [muc=
h of] the upside of stocks, but no downside=E2=80=9D is a clean and satisfy=
ing pitch. The shape of the payoff graph is pleasing.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32129843.264407/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21=
iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDctMTgvZXRmLXRoYXQtb2ZmZXJzLTEwMC1kb3=
duc2lkZS1wcm90ZWN0aW9uLWR1cmluZy1zZWxsb2Zmcy1pcy1tYWtpbmctaXRzLWRlYnV0P2Ntc=
GlkPUJCRDA3MTkyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdz=
bGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDcxOSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b=
8524a319a23cB1b6874eb" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targe=
t=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: s=
olid; background-color: #ccc;">Vildana Hajric and Emily Graffeo report</a>:=
</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The pioneer of the world=E2=80=99s first =E2=
=80=9Cbuffer ETFs=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 exchange-traded funds that are suppose=
d to limit losses during market selloffs =E2=80=94 has launched a new produ=
ct which it says offers investors complete downside protection.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Investors in the $7.5 trillion ETF universe ca=
n now put money behind the Innovator Equity Defined Protection ETF, which b=
egan trading under the ticker TJUL on Tuesday. The offering comes from Inno=
vator Capital Management, which launched the first so-called buffer ETFs, a=
lso sometimes referred to as defined-outcome funds, in 2018.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Buffer funds, as the name suggests, offer buff=
ered exposure to stocks by limiting investors=E2=80=99 downside risk while =
also capping upside potential. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yet, Innovator says that its TJUL fund =E2=80=
=94 which will track S&amp;P 500 returns up to a capped percentage over a t=
wo-year period =E2=80=94 will be the first of its kind to protect against 1=
00% of stock losses. TJUL=E2=80=99s cap on potential gains is estimated at =
about 15% after fees.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Specifically, the fund will invest at least 80=
% of its net assets in options on the $423 billion SPDR S&amp;P 500 ETF Tru=
st (ticker SPY), according to the fund=E2=80=99s prospectus. TJUL can purch=
ase and sell a combination of call and put options in an effort to cushion =
against market volatility.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The outcomes set by the fund may only be reali=
zed by investors who continuously hold shares of TJUL from the first day of=
 the =E2=80=9Coutcome period=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 July 18 =E2=80=94 to the en=
d of the two-year period, which is June 30, 2025, reads the prospectus.=C2=
=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">They give you 100% of the gains up to the cap,=
 rather than 70% of uncapped gains, but same basic idea.<a class=3D"footnot=
e-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; =
display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is a reason that this product is the fir=
st of its kind: If interest rates are zero, I can=E2=80=99t invest $91 in T=
reasuries to get back $100, so I don=E2=80=99t have $9 to spend on options =
to get S&amp;P 500 upside. (I have to put, like, $99 in Treasuries, and the=
 only way to get you any meaningful upside is by giving you some downside r=
isk too.) But as interest rates have gone up, products like this look bette=
r, and so people are offering them.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of course as interest rates have gone up, prod=
ucts like this are in some sense=C2=A0<em>less attractive: </em>Putting up =
$100 and getting back $100 in two years is <em>worse=C2=A0</em>if I missed =
out on 4.75% interest than it would be if interest rates were zero.<a class=
=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-6" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !=
important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a>=C2=A0But that=E2=80=99s not the point! The point is that a trade like =
=E2=80=9CI will give you some stock upside and take 75% of the downside bet=
ween down 5% and down 20% blah blah blah=E2=80=9D is annoying and complicat=
ed, while =E2=80=9CI will give you the upside of stocks and you can=E2=80=
=99t lose any money=E2=80=9D is nice and simple and intuitively attractive.=
 =E2=80=9CBuffer fund=E2=80=9D is complicated, =E2=80=9Cstock fund but you =
can=E2=80=99t lose money=E2=80=9D has an obvious appeal.</p>
