ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 the prospectus</a>.) It goes something like this:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Fisker sold =E2=80=9Csenior convertib=
le notes due 2025=E2=80=9D to a single investor, who is not identified. The=
se notes have a face value of $340 million, but the investor got them at a =
discount, paying Fisker $300 million.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5p=
x;">The investor can convert the notes to stock, any time it wants,=C2=A0at=
 a price of $7.80 per share, a 30% premium to the $6 stock price just befor=
e the notes offering.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Also, though=
, =E2=80=9Cthe Notes amortize in nine equal [quarterly] installments starti=
ng on July=C2=A011,=C2=A02023=E2=80=9D (that is, the day after they were is=
sued). Each quarter, $37,777,777 worth of notes come due, and Fisker can el=
ect to pay them off (1) in cash at 103% of face value (i.e. $38.9 million p=
er quarter) or (2) in stock, at a special conversion price.</li>=09<li styl=
e=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The special conversion price is (1) floored at ab=
out $1.16=C2=A0per share,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-7" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important=
; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[7]</span>
</a> (2) capped at $7.80 per share (the conversion price), and (3) otherwis=
e 93% of the volume-weighted average price of Fisker=E2=80=99s stock on eit=
her the day before conversion or the five days before conversion (whichever=
 is lower).</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Starting next July, th=
e investor can choose to buy another $226.7 million of notes on the same te=
rms, and if it does the company can choose to sell it another $113.3 millio=
n of notes, for a maximum of $340 million more ($680 million total).</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The result is that, if the stock stays roughly=
 where it is today, each quarter Fisker delivers about $40.6 million worth =
of stock to the investor, which the investor can immediately sell into the =
market.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-8" style=3D"color: #00=
0000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bo=
ttom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color=
: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[8]</span>
</a> In total, Fisker gives the investor about $365.6 million worth of stoc=
k in nine quarterly installments, and the investor gives Fisker $300 millio=
n now. Fisker has the option to pay the investor back in cash instead of st=
ock if it wants (paying back a total of $350 million in cash<a class=3D"foo=
tnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-9" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration:=
 none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; b=
order-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !importa=
nt; display: inline-block;">
<span>[9]</span>
</a>), and the investor has the option of converting all of its bonds into =
stock worth even more than $365 million if the stock goes above $7.80 per s=
hare.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-10" style=3D"color: #000=
000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bot=
tom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color:=
 transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[10]</span>
</a>=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also, =E2=80=9Cthe Investor can defer an insta=
llment payment due on any installment date to another installment date and =
may, on any installment date accelerate the payment of amounts due on up to=
 an additional two times the installment payment of the Notes=E2=80=9D: The=
 investor has some additional optionality to get a lot of stock when the ge=
tting is good, or to skip some stock deliveries when it is bad.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t know who the investor is here =
or what they are thinking, but when you see a trade like this a reasonable =
guess is that the investor is not planning to convert into stock and hold i=
t as a large long-term investor in Fisker. (In fact, the investor is not=C2=
=A0<em>allowed=C2=A0</em>to do that: The notes can=E2=80=99t be converted i=
f any conversion would leave it with more than 4.99% of Fisker=E2=80=99s st=
ock, or about $112 million worth of stock at current prices.) Instead, the =
reasonable assumption is that the investor plans to get about $40.6 million=
 worth of stock each quarter and sell it, more or less immediately, at mark=
et prices, on the stock exchange; when it has finished with that, it will c=
ome back for more the next quarter.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In other words, this=C2=A0<em>is=C2=A0</em>kin=
d of an at-the-market stock offering, except that Fisker gets the money upf=
ront,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-11" style=3D"color: #000=
000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bot=
tom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color:=
 transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[11]</span>
</a>=C2=A0and the investor gets a fee of something like 20% for its efforts=
 (and for advancing the cash).</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If this sounds familiar, it is broadly similar=
 to <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32129843.26440=
7/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDItMDcvY=
mVkLWJhdGgtYmV5b25kLXNvbGQtc29tZS1zdG9jaz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNzE5MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVG=
RiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA3MTk=
mdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBdbe41b1a" itempro=
p=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"=
>    the trade that Bed Bath &amp; Beyond Inc. did</a> earlier this year to=
 sell stock. In each case, there is a weird instrument that looks like a co=
nvertible security, and a big =E2=80=9Cinvestor=E2=80=9D who is buying most=
 or all of it. But in each case, the buyer is not really set up to be a lon=
g-term investor in the company: The investor=C2=A0is getting the stock in i=
nstallments, at a discount to market value, and selling each installment to=
 retail investors on the stock exchange.=C2=A0And the investor is getting p=
aid a nice fee for structuring the trade, giving the company=C2=A0the money=
 upfront, and generally obscuring what is happening. =E2=80=9CWe are sellin=
g $365 million of stock to retail investors to raise $300 million=E2=80=9D =
just <em>sounds </em>less good than =E2=80=9Cwe are selling a $340 million =
convertible with a 30% conversion premium to a big investor.=E2=80=9D</p>
