crypto incumbents are New FTX and New Terra, while their founders are in pr=
ison?=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That would be funny? I think a lot about a dyn=
amic among startup founders: High-profile founders tend to make grandiose p=
romises and claims that do not quite match reality, and then either (1) it =
works out and they are hailed as visionary geniuses or (2) it doesn=E2=80=
=99t and they are arrested.=C2=A0It would be odd if crypto found a third op=
tion, where the founders are arrested but it all ultimately works out.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of course FTX and Terra manifestly did <em>not=
=C2=A0</em>work out, in that they collapsed and cost their investors a lot =
of money. If you are an ambitious crypto person and you want to build the w=
orld=E2=80=99s leading crypto exchange or whatever-Terra-is, if you want to=
 =E2=80=9Cprovide real utility=E2=80=9D and attract a lot of users and inve=
stors =E2=80=A6=C2=A0wouldn=E2=80=99t it be better to start from zero? Inst=
ead of starting way in the hole, like Terra and FTX are?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Part of the issue is that both FTX and Terra i=
ssued=C2=A0<em>tokens</em>, and the best way to recover value for their cus=
tomers is to make those tokens valuable again. If FTX restarts successfully=
, then its FTT tokens will be valuable again, and FTX has tons of those tok=
ens and can use them to pay back its customers. There is some built-in base=
 of investors who (1) were (allegedly) defrauded by the company but (2) are=
 incentivized to root for its success. Still it feels like a weird marketin=
g pitch.</p>
