money into Treasuries.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-6" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[6] Also the cap is less attractive with highe=
r rates. If the two-year risk-free rate is 4.75% and the equity risk premiu=
m is 6%, then over two years the expected return on the S&amp;P 500 is some=
thing like 22.7%, meaning that your capped 15% return would be disappointin=
g. </p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-7" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[7] The floor price is not stated in the prosp=
ectus, but the prospectus covers =E2=80=9Cup to 293,103,448 shares of Class=
 A Common Stock issuable from time to time upon conversion or otherwise und=
er the Notes, assuming conversion at a conversion price equal to the Floor =
Price,=E2=80=9D and if you divide $340 million by 293.1 million you get abo=
ut $1.16.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-8" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[8] =E2=80=9CImmediately=E2=80=9D understates =
it: The rational move for the investor is to sell the stock into the market=
 *before* each amortization date, over the one- or five-day VWAP period. Yo=
u sell the stock short, trying to match the VWAP; you realize exactly $40.6=
 million on your sales; you exercise and get exactly enough stock to close =
out your short. The choice of one- or five-day VWAP gives you some flexibil=
ity to sell quickly (if the volume supports it) or slowly (if it doesn=E2=
=80=99t). These days Fisker=E2=80=99s stock trades about $48 million per da=
y, so you=E2=80=99d want at least five days to sell your $40.6 million of s=
tock, and it might take you a bit longer (that is, you might not plan to pe=
rfectly hedge before converting). The choice also gives you some extra opti=
onality: If you sell over five days and the one-day VWAP is lower, you get =
some bonus stock.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-9" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[9] That is, the $340 million face amount time=
s 103% of face amount for cash amortization payments.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-10" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ita=
lic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[10] Actually the stock has to get to about $8=
.39 for this to be a good deal for the investor: Converting at $7.80 per sh=
are gets you 43.6 million shares ($340 million divided by $7.80), whereas c=
onverting at 93% of market value gets you $365.6 million worth of stock, an=
d $365.6 divided by 43.6 is $8.39. </p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-11" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ita=
lic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[11] This gives it a bit more certainty of pro=
ceeds than a regular ATM would give it: If the stock goes way down, it stil=
l has the money. But not much more: There are a lot of conditions and coven=
ants, and if the stock does go way down there=E2=80=99s a decent chance Fis=
ker will have to pay the investor back in cash rather than stock. There is =
also a covenant that Fisker =E2=80=9C will maintain a balance of available =
cash (as defined in the Notes) equal to or greater than $340,000,000,=E2=80=
=9D so it can=E2=80=99t exactly blow through all the cash it raised before =
the two-year period is up.</p>
</div>
